  "title": "BCIT Speed Control",
  "description": "The BCIT Speed Control dataset comprises extended time-on-task EEG recordings from subjects performing simulated driving tasks designed to assess fatigue-related performance changes. Participants completed two 45-minute driving conditions with varying levels of control responsibility while experiencing periodic vehicle perturbations. The dataset includes 64-channel EEG data plus 8 additional channels (4 EOG and 2 mastoid channels) recorded at 2048 Hz sampling rate, vehicle performance metrics, and behavioral measures of fatigue, providing a resource for investigating brain-behavior interactions and fatigue biomarkers in sustained attention tasks.",
  "methods_description": "EEG data were acquired using BioSemi 64-channel systems (plus 8 additional channels including 4 eye and 2 mastoid channels) at 2048 Hz sampling rate. Subjects performed two counterbalanced Speed Control driving conditions (A: steering only with automatic speed control; B: steering and manual speed control) in a driving simulator (Real Time Technologies) with 900 Hz video refresh rate. Vehicle data were logged at 100 Hz. Participants completed a 10-15 minute practice session prior to the experimental task. Fatigue was assessed using Task-Induced Fatigue Scale (TIFS), Karolinska Sleepiness Scale (KSS), and Visual Analog Scale of Fatigue (VAS-F).",
